1. Definition

A temporary table is a table created in the database to store data temporarily during a session. It behaves like a regular table
but is automatically removed when the session ends.

2. Purpose

Temporary tables are used to:

Store intermediate query results
Avoid recalculating the same data multiple times
Simplify complex queries by breaking them into steps
Enable reuse of data across multiple queries

3. Syntax
Create Temporary Table
CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE table_name AS

SELECT ...
Query Temporary Table

SELECT * FROM table_name;

Drop Temporary Table (optional)
DROP TEMPORARY TABLE table_name;

4. Usage Workflow
Create the temporary table using a SELECT query
Use the table in one or more subsequent queries
The table is automatically removed at the end of the session

5. Key Characteristics
Exists only during the database session
Accessible only within the session in which it is created
Not visible to other users or connections
Data is stored temporarily and not persisted

6. Scope and Access
Temporary tables are session-specific
Other users or sessions on the same server cannot access them
For shared access, permanent tables or (views) must be used

practice_queries

--  Create Temporary Table---------------------------------------------------------------
CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE customer_total AS     --------This table now exists separately, like a real table (but temporary)-----------------------
SELECT customer_id, SUM(amount) AS total_spent
FROM payment
GROUP BY customer_id;

=>Explaination
Takes data from the payment table
Groups it by customer_id
Calculates total spending using SUM(amount)
Stores the result in a new temporary table called customer_total

-- Use Temporary Table--------------------------------------------
SELECT customer_id, total_spent
FROM customer_total
WHERE total_spent > 200;
 -- Drop table ------------------------------------------------------

DROP TEMPORARY TABLE customer_total;

-- 2 Store all payments above 5
CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE high_payment AS
SELECT customer_id, amount
FROM payment
WHERE amount > 5;

select * from high_payment;

drop temporary table high_payment;

-- Top 5 customers by spending---------------------------------------
create temporary table total_spending as
select customer_id, SUM(amount) as total_amt
from payment
group by customer_id;

select customer_id, total_amt
from total_spending
order by total_amt desc;



